Let’s be honest—sometimes you just want fresh, warm breadsticks right now without waiting around for yeast to do its thing. Whether you’re short on time, out of yeast, or just not in the mood for the whole rising-and-proofing process, this no-yeast breadstick recipe has your back.
It’s quick, simple, and still delivers that satisfying soft-but-slightly-crispy texture we all love. Best of all? You likely have everything you need sitting in your kitchen already.
Why Go Yeast-Free?
Before we dive into the recipe, let’s talk about why you might want to skip the yeast:
Time-saving: No need to wait for dough to rise.
Beginner-friendly: If baking with yeast intimidates you, this is a great alternative.
Fewer ingredients: No fancy extras—just pantry staples.
Now, onto the good stuff.

 No-Yeast Breadsticks Recipe
Ingredients:
2 cups all-purpose flour (plus extra for dusting)
1 tablespoon baking powder
1 teaspoon salt
1 tablespoon olive oil (plus more for brushing)
¾ cup warm water
Optional: garlic powder, Italian seasoning, grated Parmesan, or melted butter for extra flavor
Instructions:
Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C) and line a baking sheet with parchment paper or lightly grease it.
Mix dry ingredients: In a large bowl, combine the flour, baking powder, and salt. If you’re feeling fancy, throw in a teaspoon of garlic powder or Italian herbs here.
Add wet ingredients: Stir in the olive oil and warm water. Mix until a dough starts to form. It should be soft and a little sticky, but not too wet. If it’s too dry, add a tiny splash of water; too wet, dust in a little more flour.
Knead gently: On a lightly floured surface, knead the dough for just 1–2 minutes until it comes together smoothly.
Shape the sticks: Divide the dough into 10–12 pieces and roll each one into a rope about 6–8 inches long. Place them on your baking sheet with a little space between each.
Brush and bake: Brush the tops with olive oil or melted butter. Sprinkle with a pinch of salt, Parmesan, or herbs if you like. Bake for 15–18 minutes, or until golden on top and lightly crisp on the outside.
Serve warm: These are best fresh out of the oven, dipped in marinara, garlic butter, or even hummus if you’re feeling adventurous.

Tips & Twists
Make them cheesy: Add shredded cheese to the dough or sprinkle it on top before baking.
Go sweet: Skip the savory seasonings and brush with butter, then sprinkle cinnamon and sugar for a dessert-style twist.
Make ahead: You can prep the dough in advance and refrigerate for a few hours—just let it come to room temp before baking.

